The start symbol expands as  
S → NT27 NT43  

Because the grammar is in Chomsky normal form, the expansion of NT27 will yield a (possibly empty‑free) sequence of terminals, followed by exactly one terminal produced by NT43, since NT43 only has rules of the form  

NT43 → 't133' | 't16' | 't40'  

Hence the very last token of any string in the language must be one of {t133, t16, t40}.  
The given string ends with t137, which is not among these possibilities.  

Therefore the grammar cannot generate the provided string.
